(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
Jessica R. A. Hamilton, Executive Editor on the Editorial Board of the Connecticut Law Review, April 2012, Connecticut Law Review Volume 44 Number 4, “FINDING NEW POWER IN THE WIND, THE EARTH, AND THE SUN: A SURVEY OF THE REGULATION OF ALTERNATIVE ENERGY GENERATED ON AMERICAN INDIAN RESERVATIONS IN THE UNITED STATES AND FIRST NATION RESERVES IN CANADA,” [DLP PRE] [Language edited – Indigenized]&#xD;
&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
What is most critical to the creation of alternative energy projects, however, is&#xD;
&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
AND&#xD;
&#xD;
(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
too heavily on land-use intensive generation facilities, like biopower.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)137&#xD;
&#xD;
(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)&#xD;
==== Indigenous people can&amp;#39;t access electricity now and only get it by paying exorbitant prices to exploitative developers from outside the community ====&#xD;
